	   <tr><td colspan=2>Bhert,<br><br>Here are a few answers to your questions (I am answering only because you are French Canadian and not French French &amp;#61514; ).<br><br>-I started on a 56k modem and it worked fine.&nbsp;&nbsp;  Sometimes, zoning might take a little extra.  Overall, it is no big deal (although my DSL is better)<br><br>-The map coordinates are not unique to each zone.  So, each map will have a (0,0,0,) location.<br><br>-Every level you get 5 skill points.  Go to a trainer (in the guild of your home city, or scattered around other cities).  Right click on them and you will get a menu.  Pick whatever skills you want from those you can.  Some have level requirements and some cost money.  As a rule, don’t put too many points into skills you use a lot (weapons for a warrior, evocation for a wizard, etc).  They will go up on their own every fight.  Just put a few in to get started.<br><br>-Languages are learned like any other skill.  Go to a trainer to learn the first point or two.  Then change languages by going to the chat window (right-clicking on the center bottom of the screen, where all the messages scroll).  As you use the new language, it goes up.<br><br>-Binding is permanent until you bind elsewhere.  When you move around a lot, it is usually wise to bind at the nearest city.<br><br>-I have never seen anyone get banned, but I imagine it is from breaking the rules shown in the instruction books (cursing, using obscene language, etc.).  You can play an idiot (stealing money, conning other people, being annoying, etc.), but as long as you do it cleanly, you are ok.<br><br>Hope some of this helped,<br>Tibayn<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Larrymichaelson = 30th Human Wizard<br>Tibayn = 28th Vah Sir Beastlord<br>Haarbinjer = 4th Erud Necro</td></tr>
